# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: latex-typesetting
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] This page contains references to core documentation about LaTeX written by the LaTeX team.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] Articles on specific topics, talks, etc. can be found on the publication page indexed by topic.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] In addition pointer to documentation in other languages (usually developed and maintained by user groups) is given.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] To find documentation that is available elsewhere on the net, visit the links page.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] Also, there's a whole page dedicated to books on LaTeX and related topics.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] If you know about a good resource of TeX and related documentation not listed here or on the links page, please contact us.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] The original guide describing commands introduced with LaTeX2e in 1994 (with some focus on the differences between the old LaTeX 2.09 and current standard LaTeX2e) is available as well.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] For more extensive introductory documentation take a look at the links to contributed documentation that have their own page.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] The hook management introduced in 2020 is largely intended for package developers.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] However, most of the available hooks can also be useful for document authors.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] The new mark mechanism introduced in 2022 offers arbitrary many independent marks and resolves the issues with LaTeX legacy marks (available through `\markbox` and `\markright`).
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] The old mechanism remains available so that classes using it continue to work without any updates.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] Yukitoshi FUJIMURA kindly translated two of the above documents to the Japanese language.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] Here are his comments on the translation.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] There is also a Chinese translation as a browser document that can be found at https://www.cnoctave.top/2.html.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] Changes made to the LaTeX kernel or to core packages maintained by the LaTeX team are discussed in some detail in the LaTeX News Newsletters that come as part of each release.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] A document with all available issues bundled together in their historical order is `ltnews.pdf`.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] The full documentation of the source code with all commands and their implementation can be obtained by processing `source2e.tex` distributed as part of the LaTeX2e distribution.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] In 2015 we introduced a roll-back/roll-forward functionality by which it becomes possible to reset the kernel code (though not external packages at this stage) to the behavior that it had on a particular date.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] This can be useful when processing older documents.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] There is a lot of documentation in languages other than English.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] Lists of books and other resources in other languages are maintained by TeX user groups in the respective countries.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] List of books on LaTeX in English, French, German, and Spanish.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] Links to contributed documentation, tutorials, videos, communities, etc.
[src:latex-typesetting/documentation] Get LaTeX for Linux, Mac OS X, Windows and Online.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] LaTeX was originally written in the early 1980s by Leslie Lamport at SRI International.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] The current version is LaTeX2e, first released in 1994 and incrementally updated since 2015.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] This update policy replaced earlier plans for a separate release of LaTeX3, which had been in development since 1989.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] LaTeX is free software and is distributed under the LaTeX Project Public License (LPPL).
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] Like TeX, LaTeX started as a writing tool for mathematicians and computer scientists, but from early in its development, it has also been taken up by scholars who needed to write documents that include complex math expressions or non-Latin scripts, such as Arabic, Devanagari, and Chinese.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] In the early 1980s, Leslie Lamport was working at SRI, where he needed to write TeX macros for his own use.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] He thought that with a little extra effort, he could make a general package usable by others.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] Having done so, he released versions of his LaTeX macros in 1984 and 1985.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] Peter Gordon, an editor at Addison-Wesley, convinced Lamport to write a LaTeX user's manual for publication.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] Lamport was initially skeptical that anyone would pay money for it, but it came out in 1986 and sold hundreds of thousands of copies.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] On 21 August 1989, at a TeX Users Group (TUG) meeting at Stanford, Lamport agreed to turn over maintenance and development of LaTeX to Frank Mittelbach.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] Mittelbach, along with Chris Rowley and Rainer Schöpf, formed the LaTeX3 team; in 1994, they released LaTeX2e, the current standard version.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] LaTeX3 has been discontinued as a separate format; since 2018, it has been a programming layer within LaTeX2e.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] LaTeX attempts to follow the design philosophy of separating presentation from content, so that authors can focus on the content of what they are writing without attending simultaneously to its visual appearance.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] In preparing a LaTeX document, the author specifies the logical structure using commands such as *chapter*, *section*, *table*, *figure*, etc., and lets the LaTeX system handle the formatting and layout of these structures.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] As a result, it encourages the separation of the layout from the content – while still allowing manual typesetting adjustments whenever needed.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] This concept is similar to the mechanism by which many word processors allow styles to be defined globally for an entire document, or the use of Cascading Style Sheets in styling HyperText Markup Language (HTML) documents.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] The LaTeX system is a markup language that handles typesetting and rendering, and can be arbitrarily extended by using the underlying macro language to develop custom macros such as new environments and commands.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] To create a document in LaTeX, a user first creates a file, such as `document.tex`, typically using a text editor.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] The user then gives their `document.tex` file as input to the TeX program (with the LaTeX macros loaded), which prompts TeX to write out a file suitable for onscreen viewing or printing.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] This write-format-preview cycle is one of the chief ways in which working with LaTeX differs from the What-You-See-Is-What-You-Get (WYSIWYG) style of document editing.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] It is similar to the code-compile-execute cycle known to computer programmers.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] Today, many LaTeX-aware editing programs make this cycle a simple matter through the pressing of a single key while showing the output preview on the screen beside the input window.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] Some online LaTeX editors even automatically refresh the preview, while other online tools provide incremental editing in-place, mixed in with the preview in a single window.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] The name is printed in running text with a typographical logo: LaTeX.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] In media where the logo cannot be precisely reproduced in running text, the word is typically given the unique capitalization LaTeX.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] Alternatively, the TeX, LaTeX, and XeTeX logos can also be rendered via pure CSS and XHTML for use in graphical web browsers – by following the specifications of the internal `\LaTeX` macro.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] As a macro package, LaTeX provides a set of macros for TeX to interpret.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] There are many other macro packages for TeX, including Plain TeX, AMSTeX, Chemfig, chemmacros, PSTricks, PSfrag, and ConTeXt.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] When TeX "compiles" a document, it follows (from the user's point of view) the following processing sequence: Macros → TeX → Driver → Output.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] Different implementations of each of these steps are typically available in TeX distributions.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] Traditional TeX will output a DVI file, which is usually converted to a PostScript file.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] In 2000, Hàn Thế Thành and others wrote an implementation of TeX called pdfTeX, which also outputs to PDF and takes advantage of features available in that format.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] The XeTeX engine developed by Jonathan Kew, on the other hand, merges modern font technologies and Unicode with TeX.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] LuaTeX is an extended version of pdfTeX using Lua as an embedded scripting language.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] LaTeX documents (`*.tex`) can be opened with any text editor.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] They consist of plain text and contain no hidden formatting codes or binary information.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] TeX documents can also be shared by rendering the LaTeX file to other formats such as OpenDocument, XML, or class (`*.cls`) files.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] LaTeX can also (and commonly is) rendered to PDF files using the LaTeX extension pdfLaTeX.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] LaTeX files containing Unicode text can be processed into PDFs with the `inputenc` package, or by the TeX extensions XeLaTeX and LuaLaTeX.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] LaTeX has become the de facto standard to typeset mathematical expression in scientific documents.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] Hence, there are several conversion tools focusing on mathematical LaTeX expressions, such as converters to MathML or Computer Algebra System.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] LaTeX is typically distributed along with plain TeX under a free software licence: the LaTeX Project Public License (LPPL).
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] The LPPL is Debian Free Software Guidelines (DFSG) compliant as of version 1.3.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] As free software, LaTeX is available on most operating systems.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] LaTeX2e is the current version of LaTeX, since it replaced LaTeX 2.09 in 1994.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] As of 2020, LaTeX3, which started in the early 1990s, is under a long-term development project.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] Planned features include improved syntax (separation of content from styling), hyperlink support, a new user interface, access to arbitrary fonts and a new documentation.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] Some LaTeX3 features are available in LaTeX2e using packages, and by 2020 many features have been enabled in LaTeX2e by default for a gradual transition.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] There are many commercial implementations of the entire TeX system.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] System vendors may add extra features like added typefaces and telephone support.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] LyX is a free software, WYSIWYM visual document processor that uses LaTeX for a back-end.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] TeXmacs is a free, WYSIWYG editor with similar functionalities as LaTeX, but with a different typesetting engine.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] Other WYSIWYG editors that produce LaTeX include Scientific Word on Windows and macOS.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] Many community-supported TeX distributions are available.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] LaTeX is widely used in academia for the communication and publication of scientific documents and technical note-taking in many fields, owing partially to its support for complex mathematical notation.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] It also has a prominent role in the preparation and publication of books and articles that contain complex multilingual materials, such as Arabic and Greek.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] LaTeX uses the TeX typesetting program for formatting its output, and is itself written in the TeX macro language.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] LaTeX can be used as a standalone document preparation system or as an intermediate format.
[src:latex-typesetting/latex] In the latter role, for example, it is sometimes used as part of a pipeline for translating DocBook and other XML-based formats for PDF.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] TeX is widely used in academia, especially in mathematics, computer science, economics, political science, engineering, linguistics, physics, statistics, and quantitative psychology.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] It has long since displaced Unix troff (the previously favored formatting system) in most Unix installations (although *troff* still remains as the default formatter of the UNIX documentation).
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] It is also used for many other typesetting tasks, especially as the basis for LaTeX, ConTeXt, and other macro packages.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] TeX is free software, which made it accessible to a wide range of users.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] When the first paper volume of Knuth's *The Art of Computer Programming* was published in 1968, it was typeset using hot metal typesetting on a Monotype machine.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] This method, dating back to the 19th century, produced a "classic style" appreciated by Knuth.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] When the second edition was published, in 1976, the whole book had to be typeset again because the Monotype technology had been largely replaced by phototypesetting, and the original fonts were no longer available.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] When Knuth received the galley proofs of the new book on 30 March 1977, he found them inferior.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Disappointed, Knuth set out to design his own typesetting system.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Knuth saw for the first time the output of a high-quality digital typesetting system, and became interested in digital typography.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] On 13 May 1977, he wrote a memo to himself describing the basic features of TeX.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] He planned to finish it on his sabbatical in 1978 (though ultimately the language's syntax was not frozen until 1989).
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Guy Steele happened to be at Stanford during the summer of 1978, when Knuth was developing his first version of TeX.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] When Steele returned to the Massachusetts Institute of Technology that autumn, he rewrote TeX's input/output (I/O) to run under the Incompatible Timesharing System (ITS) operating system.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The first version of TeX, called TeX78, was written in the SAIL programming language to run on a PDP-10 under Stanford's WAITS operating system.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] For later versions of TeX, Knuth invented the concept of literate programming, a way of producing compilable source code and cross-linked documentation typeset in TeX from the same original file.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The language used is called WEB and produces programs in DEC PDP-10 Pascal.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] TeX82, a new version of TeX rewritten from scratch, was published in 1982.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Among other changes, the original hyphenation algorithm was replaced by a new algorithm written by Frank Liang.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] TeX82 also uses fixed-point arithmetic instead of floating-point, to ensure reproducibility of the results across different computer hardware, and includes a real, Turing-complete programming language, following intense lobbying by Guy Steele.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] In 1989, Donald Knuth released new versions of TeX and Metafont.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Despite his desire to keep the program stable, Knuth realized that 128 different characters for the text input were not enough to accommodate foreign languages; the main change in version 3.0 of TeX is thus the ability to work with 8-bit inputs, allowing 256 different characters in the text input.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Since version 3, TeX has used an idiosyncratic version numbering system, where updates have been indicated by adding an extra digit at the end of the decimal, so that the version number asymptotically approaches π.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] This is a reflection of the fact that TeX is now very stable, and only minor updates are anticipated.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The current version of TeX is 3.141592653; it was last updated in 2021.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The design was frozen after version 3.0, and no new feature or fundamental change will be added, so all newer versions will contain only bug fixes.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Even though Donald Knuth himself has suggested a few areas in which TeX could have been improved, he indicated that he firmly believes that having an unchanged system that will produce the same output now and in the future is more important than introducing new features.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] For this reason, he has stated that the "absolutely final change (to be made after my death)" will be to change the version number to π, at which point all remaining "bugs" will become "features".
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Likewise, versions of Metafont after 2.0 asymptotically approach e (currently at 2.7182818), and a similar change will be applied after Knuth's death.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] English speakers often pronounce it /tɛk/, like the first syllable of *technical*.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Knuth instructs that it be typeset with the "E" below the baseline and reduced spacing between the letters.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] This is done, as Knuth mentions in his *TeXbook*, to distinguish TeX from other system names such as TEX, the Text EXecutive processor (developed by Honeywell Information Systems).
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] TeX commands commonly start with a backslash and are grouped with curly braces.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Almost all of TeX's syntactic properties can be changed on the fly, which makes TeX input hard to parse by anything but TeX itself.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] TeX is a macro- and token-based language: many commands, including most user-defined ones, are expanded on the fly until only unexpandable tokens remain, which are then executed.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Expansion itself is practically free from side effects.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Tail recursion of macros takes no memory, and if-then-else constructs are available.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] This makes TeX a Turing-complete language even at the expansion level.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The system can be divided into four levels: in the first, characters are read from the input file and assigned a category code (sometimes called "catcode", for short).
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Combinations of a backslash (actually, any character of category zero) followed by letters (characters of category 11) or a single other character are replaced by a control-sequence token.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] In this sense, this stage is like lexical analysis, although it does not form numbers from digits.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] In the next stage, expandable control sequences (such as conditionals or defined macros) are replaced by their replacement text.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The input for the third stage is then a stream of characters (including the ones with special meaning) and unexpandable control sequences (typically assignments and visual commands).
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Here, the characters get assembled into a paragraph, and TeX's paragraph breaking algorithm works by optimizing breakpoints over the whole paragraph.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The fourth stage breaks the vertical list of lines and other material into pages.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The TeX system has precise knowledge of the sizes of all characters and symbols, and using this information, it computes the optimal arrangement of letters per line and lines per page.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] It then produces a DVI file ("DeVice Independent") containing the final locations of all characters.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] This DVI file can then be printed directly given an appropriate printer driver, or it can be converted to other formats.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Nowadays, pdfTeX is often used, which bypasses DVI generation altogether.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The base TeX system understands about 300 commands, called *primitives*.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] These low-level commands are rarely used directly by users, and most functionality is provided by format files (predumped memory images of TeX after large macro collections have been loaded).
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Knuth's original default format, which adds about 600 commands, is Plain TeX.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The most widely used format is LaTeX, originally developed by Leslie Lamport, which incorporates document styles for books, letters, slides, etc., and adds support for referencing and automatic numbering of sections and equations.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Another widely used format, AMS-TeX, is produced by the American Mathematical Society and provides many more user-friendly commands, which can be altered by journals to fit with their house style.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Most of the features of AMS-TeX can be used in LaTeX by using the "AMS packages" (e.g., `amsmath`, `amssymb`) and the "AMS document classes" (e.g., `amsart`, `amsbook`).
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Other formats include ConTeXt, used primarily for desktop publishing and written mostly by Hans Hagen at Pragma.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The TeX software incorporates several aspects that were not available, or were of lower quality, in other typesetting programs at the time when TeX was released.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Some of the innovations are based on interesting algorithms, and have led to several theses for Knuth's students.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] While some of these discoveries have now been incorporated into other typesetting programs, others, such as the rules for mathematical spacing, are still unique.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Since the primary goal of the TeX language is high-quality typesetting for publishers of books, Knuth gave a lot of attention to the spacing rules for mathematical formulae.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Knuth looked closely at these printed papers to sort out a set of rules for spacing.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] While TeX provides some basic rules and the tools needed to specify proper spacing, the exact parameters depend on the font used to typeset the formula.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] For example, the spacing for Knuth's Computer Modern fonts has been precisely fine-tuned over the years and is now set; but when other fonts, such as AMS Euler, were used by Knuth for the first time, new spacing parameters had to be defined.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The typesetting of math in TeX is not without criticism, particularly with respect to technical details of the font metrics, which were designed in an era when significant attention was paid to storage requirements.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] This resulted in some "hacks" overloading some fields, which in turn required other "hacks".
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] On an aesthetics level, the rendering of radicals has also been criticized.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The OpenType math font specification largely borrows from TeX, but has some new features/enhancements.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] In comparison with manual typesetting, the problem of justification is easy to solve with a digital system such as TeX, which, provided that good points for line breaking have been defined, can automatically spread the spaces between words to fill in the line.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The problem is thus to find the set of breakpoints that will give the most visually pleasing result.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Many line-breaking algorithms use a greedy algorithm, where the breakpoints for each line are determined one after the other, and no breakpoint is changed after it has been chosen.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Such a system is not able to define a breakpoint depending on the effect that it will have on the following lines.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] In comparison, TeX utilizes a globally optimizing line-breaking algorithm developed by Donald Knuth and Michael Plass that considers all the possible breakpoints in a paragraph.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Formally, the algorithm defines a value called *badness* associated with each possible line break; the badness is increased if the spaces on the line must stretch or shrink too much to make the line the correct width.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Penalties are added if a breakpoint is particularly undesirable: for example, if a word must be hyphenated, if two lines in a row are hyphenated, or if a very loose line is immediately followed by a very tight line.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The algorithm will then find the breakpoints that will minimize the sum of squares of the badness (including penalties) of the resulting lines.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] If the paragraph contains n possible breakpoints, the number of situations that must be evaluated naively is $2^{n}$ .
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] However, by using the method of dynamic programming, the complexity of the algorithm can be brought down to $O(n^{2})$ (see Big O notation).
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Further simplifications (for example, not testing extremely unlikely breakpoints such as a hyphenation in the first word of a paragraph, or very overfull lines) lead to an efficient algorithm whose running time is $O(nw)$ , where w is the width of a line.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] A similar algorithm is used to determine the best way to break paragraphs across two pages, in order to avoid widows or orphans (lines that appear alone on a page while the rest of the paragraph is on the following or preceding page).
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] However, in general, a thesis by Michael Plass shows how the page-breaking problem can be NP-complete because of the added complication of placing figures.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] TeX's line-breaking algorithm has been adopted by several other programs, such as Adobe InDesign (a desktop publishing application) and the GNU fmt Unix command line utility.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] If no suitable line break can be found for a line, the system will try to hyphenate a word.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The original version of TeX used a hyphenation algorithm based on a set of rules for the removal of prefixes and suffixes of words, and for deciding if it should insert a break between the two consonants in a pattern of the form vowel–consonant–consonant–vowel (which is possible most of the time).
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] TeX82 introduced a new hyphenation algorithm, designed by Frank Liang in 1983, to assign priorities to breakpoints in letter groups.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] A list of hyphenation patterns is first generated automatically from a corpus of hyphenated words (a list of 50,000 words).
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] If TeX must find the acceptable hyphenation positions in the word *encyclopedia*, for example, it will consider all the subwords of the extended word *.encyclopedia.*, where *.* is a special marker to indicate the beginning or end of the word.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The list of subwords includes all the subwords of length 1 (*.*, *e*, *n*, *c*, *y*, etc.), of length 2 (*.e*, *en*, *nc*, etc.), etc., up to the subword of length 14, which is the word itself, including the markers.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] TeX will then look into its list of hyphenation patterns, and find subwords for which it has calculated the desirability of hyphenation at each position.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] In the case of our word, 11 such patterns can be matched, namely 1c4l4, 1cy, 1d4i3a, 4edi, e3dia, 2i1a, ope5d, 2p2ed, 3pedi, pedia4, y1c.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] For each position in the word, TeX will calculate the *maximum value* obtained among all matching patterns, yielding en1cy1c4l4o3p4e5d4i3a4.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Finally, the acceptable positions are those indicated by an odd number, yielding the acceptable hyphenations *en-cy-clo-pe-di-a*.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] This system based on subwords allows the definition of very general patterns (such as 2i1a), with low indicative numbers (either odd or even), which can then be superseded by more specific patterns (such as 1d4i3a) if necessary.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] These patterns find about 90% of the hyphens in the original dictionary; more importantly, they do not insert any spurious hyphen.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] In addition, a list of exceptions (words for which the patterns do not predict the correct hyphenation) are included with the Plain TeX format; additional ones can be specified by the user.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Metafont, not strictly part of TeX, is a font description system which allows the designer to describe characters algorithmically.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] It uses Bézier curves in a fairly standard way to generate the actual characters to be displayed, but Knuth devotes substantial attention to the rasterizing problem on bitmapped displays.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Another thesis, by John Hobby, further explores this problem of digitizing "brush trajectories".
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] This term derives from the fact that Metafont describes characters as having been drawn by abstract brushes (and erasers).
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] It is commonly believed that TeX is based on bitmap fonts but, in fact, these programs "know" nothing about the fonts that they are using other than their dimensions.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] It is the responsibility of the device driver to appropriately handle fonts of other types, including PostScript Type 1 and TrueType.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Computer Modern (commonly known as "the TeX font") is freely available in Type 1 format, as are the AMS math fonts.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Users of TeX systems that output directly to PDF, such as pdfTeX, XeTeX, or LuaTeX, generally never use Metafont output at all.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] TeX documents are written and programmed using an unusual macro language.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Broadly speaking, the running of this macro language involves expansion and execution stages which do not interact directly.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Expansion includes both literal expansion of macro definitions as well as conditional branching, and execution involves such tasks as setting variables/registers and the actual typesetting process of adding glyphs to boxes.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The definition of a macro not only includes a list of commands but also the syntax of the call.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] It differs with most widely used lexical preprocessors like M4, in that the body of a macro gets tokenized at definition time.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The TeX macro language has been used to write larger document production systems, most notably including LaTeX and ConTeXt.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] This might be in a file *myfile.tex*, as *.tex* is a common file extension for plain TeX files.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] By default, everything that follows a percent sign on a line is a comment, ignored by TeX.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Running TeX on this file (for example, by typing tex myfile.tex in a command-line interpreter, or by calling it from a graphical user interface) will create an output file called *myfile.dvi*, representing the content of the page in a **d**e**v**ice **i**ndependent format (DVI).
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] A DVI file could then be either viewed on screen or converted to a suitable format for any of the various printers for which a device driver existed (printer support was generally not an operating system feature at the time that TeX was created).
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Knuth has said that there is nothing inherent in TeX that requires DVI as the output format, and later versions of TeX, notably pdfTeX, XeTeX, and LuaTeX, all support output directly to PDF.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] TeX provides a different text syntax specifically for mathematical formulas.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The formula is printed in a way a person would write by hand, or typeset the equation.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] In a document, entering *mathematics mode* is done by starting with a $ symbol, then entering a formula in TeX syntax, and closing again with another of the same symbol.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Knuth explained in jest that he chose the dollar sign to indicate the beginning and end of mathematical mode in plain TeX because typesetting mathematics was traditionally supposed to be expensive.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] *Display mathematics* (mathematics presented centred on a new line) is similar but uses $$ instead of a single $ symbol.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] In several technical fields such as computer science, mathematics, engineering and physics, TeX has become a de facto standard.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Many thousands of books have been published using TeX, including books published by Addison-Wesley, Cambridge University Press, Elsevier, Oxford University Press, and Springer.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Numerous journals in these fields are produced using TeX or LaTeX, allowing authors to submit their raw manuscript written in TeX.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] While many publications in other fields, including dictionaries and legal publications, have been produced using TeX, it has not been as successful as in the more technical fields, as TeX was primarily designed to typeset mathematics.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] While such extensions have been created (including some by Knuth himself), most people have extended TeX only using macros and it has remained a system associated with technical typesetting.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Packages like mhchem, XyMTeX, chemfig, and chemmacros for typesetting chemical equations, structures, and reactions in LaTeX.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] It is possible to use TeX for automatic generation of sophisticated layout for XML data.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The differences in syntax between the two description languages can be overcome with the help of TeXML.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] In the context of XML publication, TeX can thus be considered an alternative to XSL-FO.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] TeX allowed scientific papers in mathematical disciplines to be reduced to relatively small files that could be rendered client-side, allowing fully typeset scientific papers to be exchanged over the early Internet and emerging World Wide Web, even when sending large files was difficult.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] This paved the way for the creation of repositories of scientific papers such as arXiv, through which papers could be 'published' without an intermediary publisher.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The original source code for the current TeX software is written in WEB, a mixture of documentation written in TeX and a Pascal subset in order to ensure readability and portability.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] For example, TeX does all of its dynamic allocation itself from fixed-size arrays and uses only fixed-point arithmetic for its internal calculations.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] As a result, TeX has been ported to almost all operating systems, usually by using the web2c program to convert the source code into C instead of directly compiling the Pascal code.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Knuth has kept a very detailed log of all the bugs he has corrected and changes he has made in the program since 1982; as of 2025, the list contains 440 entries, not including the version modification that should be done after his death as the final change in TeX.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Knuth offers monetary awards to people who find and report a bug in TeX.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The award per bug started at US$2.56 (one "hexadecimal dollar") and doubled every year until it was frozen at its current value of $327.68.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Knuth has lost relatively little money as there have been very few bugs claimed.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] In addition, recipients have been known to frame their check as proof that they found a bug in TeX rather than cashing it.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Due to scammers finding scanned copies of his checks on the internet and using them to try to drain his bank account, Knuth no longer sends out real checks, but those who submit bug reports can get credit at The Bank of San Serriffe instead.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] TeX is usually provided in the form of an easy-to-install bundle of TeX itself along with Metafont and all the necessary fonts, documents formats, and utilities needed to use the typesetting system.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] On UNIX-compatible systems, including Linux and Apple macOS, TeX is distributed as part of the larger TeX Live distribution.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] (Prior to TeX Live, the teTeX distribution was the de facto standard on UNIX-compatible systems.) On Microsoft Windows, there is the MiKTeX distribution (enhanced by proTeXt) and the Microsoft Windows version of TeX Live.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Several document processing systems are based on TeX, notably jadeTeX, which uses TeX as a backend for printing from James Clark's DSSSL Engine, the Arbortext publishing system, and Texinfo, the GNU documentation processing system.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] TeX has been the official typesetting package for the GNU operating system since 1984.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Most TeX extensions are available for free from CTAN, the Comprehensive TeX Archive Network.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Donald Knuth has indicated several times that the source code of TeX has been placed into the "public domain", and he strongly encourages modifications or experimentations with this source code.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] However, since Knuth highly values the reproducibility of the output of all versions of TeX, any changed version must not be called TeX, or anything confusingly similar.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] To enforce this rule, any implementation of the system must pass a test suite called the TRIP test before being allowed to be called TeX.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The question of licence is somewhat confused by the statements included at the beginning of the TeX source code, which indicate that "all rights are reserved.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Copying of this file is authorized only if ... you make absolutely no changes to your copy".
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] This restriction should be interpreted as a prohibition to change the source code *as long as the file is called tex.web*.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The copyright note at the beginning of tex.web (and mf.web) was changed in 2021 to explicitly state this.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] This interpretation is confirmed later in the source code when the TRIP test is mentioned ("If this program is changed, the resulting system should not be called 'TeX'").
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The American Mathematical Society tried in the early 1980s to claim a trademark for TeX.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] This was rejected because at the time "TEX" (all caps) was registered by Honeywell for the "Text EXecutive" text processing system.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Since the source code of TeX is essentially in the public domain, other programmers are allowed (and explicitly encouraged) to improve the system, but are required to use another name to distribute the modified TeX, meaning that the source code can still evolve.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] For example, the Omega project was developed after 1991, primarily to enhance TeX's multilingual typesetting abilities.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Knuth created "unofficial" modified versions, such as TeX-XeT, which allows a user to mix texts written in left-to-right and right-to-left writing systems in the same document.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Notable entities in the TeX community include the TeX Users Group (TUG), which currently publishes *TUGboat* and formerly published *The PracTeX Journal*, covering a wide range of topics in digital typography relevant to TeX.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The Deutschsprachige Anwendervereinigung TeX (DANTE) is a large user group in Germany.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The TeX Users Group was founded in 1980 for educational and scientific purposes, provides an organization for those who have an interest in typography and font design, and are users of the TeX typesetting system invented by Knuth.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The TeX Users Group represents the interests of TeX users worldwide.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] The TeX Users Group publishes the journal *TUGboat* three times per year; DANTE publishes *Die TeXnische Komödie* four times per year.
[src:latex-typesetting/tex] Other user groups include DK-TUG in Denmark, GUTenberg in France, GuIT in Italy, NTG in the Netherlands and UK-TUG in the United Kingdom; the user groups jointly maintain a complete list.
[src:latex-typesetting/tutorials-tugindia] Any comments or suggestions about these tutorials can be sent to tutorialteam@tug.org.in.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] One significant effect of typesetting was that authorship of works could be spotted more easily, making it difficult for copiers who have not gained permission.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] During much of the letterpress era, movable type was composed by hand for each page by workers called compositors.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] A tray with many dividers, called a case, contained cast metal *sorts*, each with a single letter or symbol, but backwards (so they would print correctly).
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The compositor assembled these sorts into words, then lines, then pages of text, which were then bound tightly together by a *chase*, making up a *form* or page.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] If done correctly, all letters were of the same height, and a flat surface of type was created.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The form was placed in a press and inked, and then printed (an impression made) on paper.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Metal type read backwards, from right to left, and a key skill of the compositor was their ability to read this backwards text.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Before computers were invented, and thus becoming computerized (or digital) typesetting, font sizes were changed by replacing the characters with a different size of type.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] In letterpress printing, individual letters and punctuation marks were cast on small metal blocks, known as "sorts," and then arranged to form the text for a page.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The size of the type was determined by the size of the character on the face of the sort.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] A compositor would need to physically swap out the sorts for a different size to change the font size.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] During typesetting, individual sorts are picked from a type case with the right hand, and set from left to right into a composing stick held in the left hand, appearing to the typesetter as upside down.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] As seen in the photo of the composing stick, a lower case 'q' looks like a 'd', a lower case 'b' looks like a 'p', a lower case 'p' looks like a 'b' and a lower case 'd' looks like a 'q'.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] This is reputed to be the origin of the expression "mind your p's and q's".
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] It might just as easily have been "mind your b's and d's".
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] A forgotten but important part of the process took place after the printing: after cleaning with a solvent the expensive sorts had to be redistributed into the typecase - called *sorting* or *dissing* - so they would be ready for reuse.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Errors in sorting could later produce *misprints* if, say, a p was put into the b compartment.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The diagram at right illustrates a cast metal sort: **a** face, **b** body or shank, **c** point size, **1** shoulder, **2** nick, **3** groove, **4** foot.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Wooden printing sorts were used for centuries in combination with metal type.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Not shown, and more the concern of the casterman, is the "set", or width of each sort.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Set width, like body size, is measured in points.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] In order to extend the working life of type, and to account for the finite sorts in a case of type, copies of forms were cast when anticipating subsequent printings of a text, freeing the costly type for other work.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] This was particularly prevalent in book and newspaper work where rotary presses required type forms to wrap an impression cylinder rather than set in the bed of a press.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] In this process, called stereotyping, the entire form is pressed into a fine matrix such as plaster of Paris or papier mâché to create a flong, from which a positive form is cast in type metal.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Advances such as the typewriter and computer would push the state of the art even farther ahead.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Still, hand composition and letterpress printing have not fallen completely out of use, and since the introduction of digital typesetting, it has seen a revival as an artisanal pursuit.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] However, it is a small niche within the larger typesetting market.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The time and effort required to manually compose the text led to several efforts in the 19th century to produce mechanical typesetting.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] While some, such as the Paige compositor, met with limited success, by the end of the 19th century, several methods had been devised whereby an operator working a keyboard or other devices could produce the desired text.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Most of the successful systems involved the in-house casting of the type to be used, hence are termed "hot metal" typesetting.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The Linotype machine, invented in 1884, used a keyboard to assemble the casting matrices, and cast an entire line of type at a time (hence its name).
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] In the Monotype system, a keyboard was used to punch a paper tape, which was then fed to control a casting machine.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The Ludlow Typograph involved hand-set matrices, but otherwise used hot metal.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] By the early 20th century, the various systems were nearly universal in large newspapers and publishing houses.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Phototypesetting or "cold type" systems first appeared in the early 1960s and rapidly displaced continuous casting machines.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] These devices consisted of glass or film disks or strips (one per font) that spun in front of a light source to selectively expose characters onto light-sensitive paper.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Originally they were driven by pre-punched paper tapes.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Later they were connected to computer front ends.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] One of the earliest electronic photocomposition systems was introduced by Fairchild Semiconductor.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The typesetter typed a line of text on a Fairchild keyboard that had no display.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] To verify correct content of the line it was typed a second time.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] If the two lines were identical a bell rang and the machine produced a punched paper tape corresponding to the text.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] With the completion of a block of lines the typesetter fed the corresponding paper tapes into a phototypesetting device that mechanically set type outlines printed on glass sheets into place for exposure onto a negative film.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Photosensitive paper was exposed to light through the negative film, resulting in a column of black type on white paper, or a galley.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The galley was then cut up and used to create a mechanical drawing or paste up of a whole page.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] A large film negative of the page is shot and used to make plates for offset printing.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The next generation of phototypesetting machines to emerge were those that generated characters on a cathode-ray tube display.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] These machines were the mainstay of phototypesetting for much of the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Such machines could be "driven online" by a computer front-end system or took their data from magnetic tape.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Type fonts were stored digitally on conventional magnetic disk drives.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Computers excel at automatically typesetting and correcting documents.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Character-by-character, computer-aided phototypesetting was, in turn, rapidly rendered obsolete in the 1980s by fully digital systems employing a raster image processor to render an entire page to a single high-resolution digital image, now known as imagesetting.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The first commercially successful laser imagesetter, able to make use of a raster image processor, was the Monotype Lasercomp.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] ECRM, Compugraphic (later purchased by Agfa) and others rapidly followed suit with machines of their own.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The descendants of these text markup languages include LaTeX, SGML, XML and HTML.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The minicomputer systems output columns of text on film for paste-up and eventually produced entire pages and signatures of 4, 8, 16 or more pages using imposition software on devices such as the Israeli-made Scitex Dolev.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The data stream used by these systems to drive page layout on printers and imagesetters, often proprietary or specific to a manufacturer or device, drove development of generalized printer control languages, such as Adobe Systems' PostScript and Hewlett-Packard's PCL.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Computerized typesetting was so rare that *BYTE* magazine (comparing itself to "the proverbial shoemaker's children who went barefoot") did not use any computers in production until its August 1979 issue used a Compugraphics system for typesetting and page layout.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The magazine did not yet accept articles on floppy disks, but hoped to do so "as matters progress".
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Before the 1980s, practically all typesetting for publishers and advertisers was performed by specialist typesetting companies.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] These companies performed keyboarding, editing and production of paper or film output, and formed a large component of the graphic arts industry.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] In the United States, these companies were located in rural Pennsylvania, New England or the Midwest, where labor was cheap and paper was produced nearby, but still within a few hours' travel time of the major publishing centers.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Improvements in software and hardware, and rapidly lowering costs, popularized desktop publishing and enabled very fine control of typeset results much less expensively than the minicomputer dedicated systems.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] At the same time, word processing systems, such as Wang, WordPerfect and Microsoft Word, revolutionized office documents.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] They did not, however, have the typographic ability or flexibility required for complicated book layout, graphics, mathematics, or advanced hyphenation and justification rules (*H and J*).
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] By 2000, this industry segment had shrunk because publishers were now capable of integrating typesetting and graphic design on their own in-house computers.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Many found the cost of maintaining high standards of typographic design and technical skill made it more economical to outsource to freelancers and graphic design specialists.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The availability of cheap or free fonts made the conversion to do-it-yourself easier, but also opened up a gap between skilled designers and amateurs.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The advent of PostScript, supplemented by the PDF file format, provided a universal method of proofing designs and layouts, readable on major computers and operating systems.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] QuarkXPress had enjoyed a market share of 95% in the 1990s, but lost its dominance to Adobe InDesign from the mid-2000s onward.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] IBM created and inspired a family of typesetting languages with names that were derivatives of the word "SCRIPT".
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Later versions of SCRIPT included advanced features, such as automatic generation of a table of contents and index, multicolumn page layout, footnotes, boxes, automatic hyphenation and spelling verification.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] NSCRIPT was a port of SCRIPT to OS and TSO from CP-67/CMS SCRIPT.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Waterloo Script was created at the University of Waterloo (UW) later.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] One version of SCRIPT was created at MIT and the AA/CS at UW took over project development in 1974.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The program was first used at UW in 1975.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] In the 1970s, SCRIPT was the only practical way to word process and format documents using a computer.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] By the late 1980s, the SCRIPT system had been extended to incorporate various upgrades.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Page numbers can be in Arabic or Roman numerals, and can appear at the top or bottom of the page, in the centre, on the left or on the right, or on the left for even-numbered pages and on the right for odd-numbered pages.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Underscoring or overstriking can be made a function of SCRIPT, thus uncomplicating editor functions.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] SCRIPT files are regular OS datasets or CMS files.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The article also pointed out SCRIPT had over 100 commands to assist in formatting documents, though 8 to 10 of these commands were sufficient to complete most formatting jobs.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Thus, SCRIPT had many of the capabilities computer users generally associate with contemporary word processors.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] SCRIPT/VS was a SCRIPT variant developed at IBM in the 1980s.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] DWScript is a version of SCRIPT for MS-DOS, named after its author, D.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Williams, but was never released to the public and only used internally by IBM.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Script is still available from IBM as part of the Document Composition Facility for the z/OS operating system.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The standard generalized markup language (SGML) was based upon IBM Generalized Markup Language (GML).
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] GML was a set of macros on top of IBM Script.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] DSSSL is an international standard developed to provide a stylesheets for SGML documents.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] XSL-FO is most often used to generate PDF files from XML files.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The arrival of SGML/XML as the document model made other typesetting engines popular.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Such engines include Datalogics Pager, Penta, Miles 33's OASYS, Xyvision's XML Professional Publisher, FrameMaker, and Arbortext.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] XSL-FO compatible engines include Apache FOP, Antenna House Formatter, and RenderX's XEP.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] These products allow users to program their SGML/XML typesetting process with the help of scripting languages.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] YesLogic's Prince is another one, which is based on CSS Paged Media.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] During the mid-1970s, Joe Ossanna, working at Bell Laboratories, wrote the troff typesetting program to drive a Wang C/A/T phototypesetter owned by the Labs; it was later enhanced by Brian Kernighan to support output to different equipment, such as laser printers.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] While its use has fallen off, it is still included with a number of Unix and Unix-like systems, and has been used to typeset a number of high-profile technical and computer books.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Some versions, as well as a GNU work-alike called groff, are now open source.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Knuth at the end of the 1970s, is another widespread and powerful automated typesetting system that has set high standards, especially for typesetting mathematics.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] LuaTeX and LuaLaTeX are variants of TeX and of LaTeX scriptable in Lua.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] TeX is considered fairly difficult to learn on its own, and deals more with appearance than structure.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The LaTeX macro package, written by Leslie Lamport at the beginning of the 1980s, offered a simpler interface and an easier way to systematically encode the structure of a document.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] LaTeX markup is widely used in academic circles for published papers and books.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Although standard TeX does not provide an interface of any sort, there are programs that do.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] These programs include Scientific Workplace and LyX, which are graphical/interactive editors; TeXmacs, while being an independent typesetting system, can also aid the preparation of TeX documents through its export capability.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] GNU TeXmacs (whose name is a combination of TeX and Emacs, although it is independent from both of these programs) is a typesetting system which is at the same time a WYSIWYG word processor.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] SILE borrows some algorithms from TeX and relies on other libraries such as HarfBuzz and ICU, with an extensible core engine developed in Lua.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] By default, SILE's input documents can be composed in a custom LaTeX-inspired markup (SIL) or in XML.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] Via the adjunction of 3rd-party modules, composition in Markdown or Djot is also possible.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] The typesetting system Typst combines a Markdown-like markup of the input and an embedded programming language with a high typographical quality of the output.
[src:latex-typesetting/typesetting] This system has been publicly available since March 2023 and was presented in July 2023 at the Tex Users Group (TUG) 2023 conference.
